sterious qualities that elevate humans to cultural significance. By situating the text in the context of six essays by distinguished scholars that reevaluate both Carlyle’s work and his ideas, David Sorensen and Brent Kinser argue that Carlyle's concept of heroism stresses the hero’s spiritual dimension. In Carlyle’s engagement with various heroic personalities, he dislodges religiosity from religion, myth from history, and truth from “quackery” as he describes the wondrous ways in which these “flowing light-fountains” unlock the heroic potential of ordinary human beings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHero worship. 0aHeroes. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAtwood, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Owen Dudley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvie, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinser, Brent E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinser, Brent E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReed, Terence James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSorensen, David R, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSorensen, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Beverly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030014860240uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014862640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300148626423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300148626/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  